1.2.1¶

In [28]:
from sklearn.linear_model import LogisticRegression 
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
x1 = df["area.se"]
x2 = df["texture.worst"]
y = df.diagnosis == "M"
X = np.column_stack((x1, x2))
m = LogisticRegression(solver="lbfgs").fit(X, y)
# Now greate the regular grid
ex1 = np.linspace(x1.min(), x1.max(), 30) # 30 elements 
ex2 = np.linspace(x2.min(), x2.max(), 30)
xx1, xx2 = np.meshgrid(ex1, ex2)
# meshgrid creates two 30x30 matrices
g = np.column_stack((xx1.ravel(), xx2.ravel()))
# we create the design matrix by stacking the xx1, xx2
# after unraveling those into columns
# predict on the grid
hatY = m.predict(g).reshape(30, 30)
# imshow wants a matrix, so we reshape the predicted 2 vector into one
_ = plt.imshow(hatY, extent=(x1.min(), x1.max(), x2.min(), x2.max()), 
               aspect="auto", # let the image fit to screen
               interpolation='none', origin='lower',
# you need to specify that the image begins from below,
           # not above, otherwise it will be flipped around
                alpha=0.3)
_ = plt.scatter(x1, x2, c=y, edgecolor='k', s=8) 
_ = plt.show()

x2n = (x2 - x2.mean())/x2.std()

m = KNeighborsClassifier(7).fit(Xn, y)

1.2.3¶

After normalizing the data, the two features are brought to the same scale, which results in the he normalied one looks different and better than original. This would helps us understand their effects earlier. Then accuracy here is better than the original one because of reason as well. The accuracy of original features is 0.712 which is smaller than the normalized features which is 0.921.

1.2.4 ow use the original (non-normalized) features and repeat the process. However, this time use Mahalanobis distance¶

In [35]:
x1 = df["texture.mean"]
x2 = df["concpoints.mean"]
y = df.diagnosis == "M"
X = np.column_stack((x1, x2))
#m = LogisticRegression(solver="lbfgs").fit(X, y)
Sigma = np.cov(X, rowvar=False)
mahalanobis_m = KNeighborsClassifier(n_neighbors=1,
                         metric="mahalanobis",
                         metric_params={"V":Sigma}).fit(X, y)
cv = cross_val_score(mahalanobis_m, X, y, cv=10) 
np.mean(cv)
Out[35]:
0.8751566416040099

1.2.6 Describe your observations.¶

How well do original/normalized/Mahalanobis-transformed features work? Does it depend on the features? Does the visual impression from images align with the cross-validation results?

The original one with 86.3% of accuracy, the accuracy for normalized one is 86.6%, and the accuarcy with Mahalanobis-transformed is 82.9%, which does depend on the features. The visual impression from images align with the cross-validation results.

The pixels records the RGB value for each data point in the images.

M reshapes the pixels from 3-d array into a 2-d array that stores the RGB information of each data point.

cl values indicate the cluster that each data point belongs to.

The the columns of center color values printed above indicates the RGB value for each centroid. The number means the RGB color number from 0 to 255.

In [50]:
len(centers)*3
Out[50]:
48

We have total of 48 center color values. We have those numbers to represent the color for each centroid.

In [51]:
def num_colors(num):
    M = pixels.reshape((-1, pixels.shape[2]))
    m = KMeans(num).fit(M)
    cl = m.predict(M)
    centers = m.cluster_centers_
    compressed = (centers[cl] / 255).reshape(pixels.shape)
    ax = plt.subplot(1,1,1)
    ax.set_aspect("equal")
    _ = plt.imshow(compressed)
    _ = plt.show()
